ce:section.ce:para:
The electrochemical corrosion behaviors of various samples were measured by an electrochemical analyzer (CH1760C, Chinstruments, Shanghai) with a three-electrode-cell (a saturated calomel electrode as the reference electrode, the tested samples as the working electrode, and a graphite rod as the counter electrode). First, the samples were immersed in 0.9 wt % NaCl solution for 400 s to acquire a steady open circuit potential. Then, the potentiodynamic polarization measurement was performed at a scanning rate of 10 mV/s, and corrosion potential (E

                           corr
                        ) and current density (j

                           corr
                        ) were calculated by Tafel extrapolation technique.

Electrochemical analysis was used to evaluate the corrosion behaviors of Ti, VG@Ti-650, and VG@Ti-750 and the results are showed in Table 1
                         and Fig. 2b. Corrosion potentials (E

                           corr
                        ) of Ti, VG@Ti-650, and VG@Ti-750 are −0.537 V, −0.361 V, and −0.316 V, respectively. Corrosion currents (j

                           corr
                        ) of Ti, VG@Ti-650, and VG@Ti-750 are 7.587 × 10−6 A cm−2, 1.371 × 10−5 A cm−2, and 1.570 × 10−5 A cm−2, respectively. The results indicate that vertical graphene increases the corrosion threshold of Ti, but raises the corrosion rate once the corrosion happens.
